    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-10-05T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-10-05T10:00:00-05:00" n="22"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">702.0641/86: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London (<persName type="from"
                            >Frazer</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-10-05T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 5, 1933—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 5—11:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Great aggravation of the serious financial plight our clerks Great Britain
                    threatened by imposition British income tax for past several years. It might
                    greatly assist them to claim reciprocal treatment as accorded same circumstances
                    by our Treasury in the United States. Does Department’s telegram addressed
                    Retallack August 28th<note n="28" xml:id="d22fn28">Not printed.</note> mean
                    Treasury Department will not tax American staffs British Consulates until period
                    beginning July 1, 1933?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Frazer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
